BOOTSTRAP STALE-LOCK WEDGE - precise root cause (witnessed 2026-06-08, gm-plugkit): both single-instance guards DO have dead-pid liveness checks, so my first theory (no liveness check) was WRONG. acquireSingleInstance (supervisor.js:74-100) uses O_EXCL wx + pidAlive(other) and unlinks if dead. acquireLock (bootstrap.js:142-167) breaks the lock if mtime>LOCK_STALE_MS(30min) OR !pidAlive(owner). The REAL hole: bootstrap.js pidAlive (line 138) returns e.code===EPERM as ALIVE - on Windows process.kill(recycledPid,0) on a recycled pid owned by another/elevated process throws EPERM, so a dead-but-recycled holder pid reads alive and the lock is never broken by the pid check. supervisor.js pidAlive (line 65) does NOT have this - it returns false on any throw incl EPERM (stricter). The two pidAlive impls are INCONSISTENT. Witnessed: 4 supervisors looped spawn->exit(another supervisor is alive) with ZERO live wrapper/supervisor procs, ensureReady hit lock wait timeout after ATTEMPT_TIMEOUT_MS(10min) on v0.1.637/.lock (mtime Jun7 18:54); manual rm of .supervisor.pid(held pid 22500) + the .lock recovered. FIX DIRECTION (needs its own focused test chain, risky to ship blind - process-liveness semantics under Windows pid-recycling): (a) unify the two pidAlive impls; (b) add a secondary liveness signal beyond bare pid - verify the held pid is actually a plugkit node/bun process (Name match) not just any pid on a recycled id, mirroring how isProfileLocked could be hardened; (c) consider shortening LOCK_STALE_MS or having the supervisor touch its pid file as a heartbeat so a truly-dead holder ages out fast. DNA P9 worst-case: our own bootstrap has a silent wedge mode requiring manual file removal - exactly the catastrophic-silent-failure the principle forbids.